{
  "root_causes": [
    {
      "type": "Missing return route (R2)",
      "cause": "R2 has no route for the 192.168.0.0/24 network, so return traffic from 172.16.0.12 to 192.168.0.12 will not be sent back to R1 and is being forwarded to R2's default next-hop instead.",
      "evidence": [
        "R2 routing config contains only a default route: \"prefix\": \"0.0.0.0\", \"fwd-list\": [{ \"fwd\": \"10.0.0.6\" }], and there is no entry for 192.168.0.0/24 (get_running_config for R2).",
        "R1 has a route to the destination network on R2: \"prefix\": \"172.16.0.0\", \"mask\": \"255.255.255.0\", \"fwd-list\": [{ \"fwd\": \"10.0.0.2\" }] (get_running_config for R1) â€” forward path from 192.168.0.12 â†’ 172.16.0.12 is configured.",
        "R1 and R2 serial link IPs match: R1 Serial0/1/0 address 10.0.0.1/30 and R2 Serial0/1/0 address 10.0.0.2/30 (get_running_config outputs), so the next-hop toward R2 is reachable/configured on both sides.",
        "Both R1 and R2 outbound ACLs include a permissive 'permit ip any any' entry (R1: access-list R1_TO_R2 seq 20 permit ip any any; R2: access-list R2_TO_R1 seq 20 permit ip any any) â€” ACLs are unlikely to be blocking ICMP between the networks."
      ],
      "confidence": 0.95
    }
  ],
  "missing_info": []
}

{
  "intent": "check_and_fix",
  "intent_description": "Source 192.168.0.12 cannot reach 172.16.0.12 because R2 lacks a return route for 192.168.0.0/24. Remediate so traffic from 172.16.0.12 is routed back to 192.168.0.12 via R1.",
  "target": "router2",
  "needs_fix": true,
  "plan": {
    "problem": "R2 has no route for 192.168.0.0/24; return traffic from 172.16.0.12 is forwarded to R2's default next-hop instead of R1.",
